  "prompt": "How can I prepare for GRE in 20 days?",
  "response": "Preparing for the GRE in just 20 days is a significant challenge and requires a focused, highly efficient, and realistic approach. It's crucial to understand that you likely won't achieve a perfect score in this timeframe, but you *can* improve your score significantly with the right strategy. Here's a plan to maximize your prep time:\n\n**I. Realistic Assessment & Goal Setting (Day 1)**\n\n1.  **Diagnostic Test:** Take a full-length GRE practice test **under timed conditions**. This is *essential*.  This will:\n    *   **Establish your baseline score:**  Know your starting point in each section (Verbal, Quant, and Analytical Writing).\n    *   **Identify your strengths and weaknesses:** Pinpoint specific question types, topics, and content areas where you struggle most.  Be honest with yourself!  This is more important than your overall score.\n    *   **Familiarize yourself with the test format and pacing:**  Understand how the test feels under pressure.\n2.  **Review Diagnostic Results:** Analyze your answers carefully.  Don't just look at correct/incorrect.  Ask yourself:\n    *   *Why* did I get this wrong? (Content gap, misunderstanding the question, careless error, timing issue?)\n    *   What specific skills am I lacking? (e.g., Vocabulary, Algebra, Reading Comprehension strategies)\n3.  **Set Realistic Score Goals:**  Research the average GRE scores for the programs you're applying to.  Set achievable goals for improvement based on your diagnostic score and the target scores.  Be realistic about how much you can improve in 20 days.  Aim for improvement, not perfection.  A 5-10 point increase in each section is a good target with focused effort.\n4.  **Gather Materials:**  Make sure you have the essential study resources:\n    *   **Official GRE materials:** The Official GRE Guide and Official GRE Quantitative/Verbal Reasoning Practice Questions are *mandatory*.  These are the *only* resources that truly replicate the test.\n    *   **A good GRE prep book or online course:** Consider Manhattan Prep, Kaplan, Magoosh, or Powerscore (consider which one suits your learning style - structured vs. adaptable).  Choose ONE. Don't try to use multiple resources; it's too time-consuming. Many offer free trial access to materials and practice questions.\n    *   **Vocabulary flashcards or app:**  (Magoosh, Memrise, Anki are good options)\n    *   **Notebook for notes and practice problems.**\n\n**II.  Targeted Study Plan (Days 2-18)**\n\n*   **Allocate Time Strategically:**  Dedicate *at least* 3-4 hours per day to GRE prep.  Evenings and weekends are crucial. Schedule your study time in advance and stick to it.\n*   **Prioritize Weaknesses:**  Focus the majority of your time on your weakest areas identified in the diagnostic test.\n*   **Alternate Subjects:**  Don't study Verbal for 8 hours straight. Switch between Verbal, Quant, and AWA to stay engaged and prevent burnout.  A good structure might be 1.5 hours of Quant, 1.5 hours of Verbal, and 30 minutes of AWA practice per day. Adjust this based on your needs.\n*   **Daily Breakdown (Example):**\n    *   **Quant:**\n        *   Review key concepts: Algebra, Geometry, Data Analysis. Focus on topics where you made mistakes on the diagnostic.\n        *   Practice problem sets: Solve a variety of problems, focusing on accuracy and understanding the underlying principles.\n        *   Analyze mistakes:  Understand *why* you made errors and how to avoid them in the future.\n    *   **Verbal:**\n        *   Vocabulary study:  Learn new words using flashcards or an app. Focus on high-frequency GRE words.\n        *   Reading Comprehension: Practice reading passages and answering questions. Focus on identifying the main idea, supporting details, and author's tone.\n        *   Text Completion and Sentence Equivalence: Practice filling in the blanks with the best words. Pay attention to context clues.\n    *   **Analytical Writing (AWA):**\n        *   Review the essay prompts and scoring criteria.\n        *   Practice writing essays: Aim for 3-4 practice essays during this period.\n        *   Review your essays: Evaluate your writing based on the scoring criteria and identify areas for improvement.\n*   **Weekly Structure:**\n    *   **Week 1:**  Foundation building. Focus on reviewing fundamental concepts and building vocabulary.\n    *   **Week 2:**  Practice and strategy. Solve practice questions, learn test-taking strategies, and refine your approach to different question types.\n    *   **Week 3:**  Simulated Tests and Review. Take full-length practice tests to assess your progress and identify areas for further improvement.\n*   **Specific Strategies:**\n    *   **Quant:**\n        *   Memorize formulas:  Know basic geometry, algebra, and statistics formulas.\n        *   Practice with real GRE questions:  Focus on the official GRE practice questions.\n        *   Learn shortcuts and strategies:  Look for efficient ways to solve problems.\n    *   **Verbal:**\n        *   Read widely:  Read articles from reputable sources (e.g., The New York Times, The Economist) to improve your reading comprehension skills.\n        *   Learn vocabulary in context:  Don't just memorize definitions. Understand how words are used in sentences.\n        *   Practice active reading:  Highlight key information and take notes while reading passages.\n    *   **AWA:**\n        *   Understand the prompt types:  Argument and Issue essays.\n        *   Practice brainstorming:  Develop strong arguments and counterarguments.\n        *   Focus on clarity and organization:  Write well-structured and easy-to-understand essays.\n\n**III. Practice Tests and Review (Days 16-18)**\n\n1.  **Full-Length Practice Tests:** Take at least *two* more full-length GRE practice tests under timed conditions. These should be spaced out. Use official ETS tests if possible.\n2.  **Thorough Review:**  After each practice test, spend a significant amount of time reviewing your answers.  Focus on:\n    *   **Understanding mistakes:**  Why did you get the question wrong?\n    *   **Identifying patterns:**  Are there specific types of questions you consistently struggle with?\n    *   **Refining strategies:**  Adjust your approach based on your performance.\n3.  **Simulate Test Conditions:**  Take the practice tests in a quiet environment, free from distractions.  Follow the official GRE rules and time limits.  This will help you build stamina and manage test anxiety.\n\n**IV.  Final Preparation (Days 19-20)**\n\n1.  **Review Weak Areas:**  Revisit your notes and practice problems in the areas where you are still struggling.\n2.  **Final Vocabulary Review:**  Quickly review your vocabulary flashcards or app.\n3.  **Mental Preparation:**  Get plenty of rest, eat healthy meals, and exercise regularly.  Visualize success and practice relaxation techniques to manage test anxiety.\n4.  **Logistics:**  Confirm your test date, time, and location.  Gather all necessary materials (ID, confirmation email).  Plan your route to the test center.\n5.  **Day Before:** Light review only.  Avoid cramming.  Focus on relaxing and getting a good night's sleep.\n\n**Key Tips for a 20-Day Sprint:**\n\n*   **Ruthless Prioritization:** You *cannot* cover everything. Focus on the highest-yield topics and question types.\n*   **Quality over Quantity:** It's better to understand a few concepts deeply than to skim over many concepts superficially.\n*   **Strategic Guessing:** Learn how to eliminate incorrect answer choices and make educated guesses. There is no penalty for incorrect answers.\n*   **Pacing is Critical:** Practice pacing yourself on each section of the test. Don't spend too much time on any one question.\n*   **Stay Positive and Motivated:**  GRE prep can be challenging, especially on a tight schedule.  Stay positive and focused on your goals.  Celebrate small victories.\n*   **Don't Compare Yourself to Others:**  Everyone learns at a different pace.  Focus on your own progress and improvement.\n*   **Get Enough Sleep:**  Lack of sleep will impair your cognitive abilities and hurt your performance.\n*   **Know the Test Format Cold:** Familiarize yourself with the instructions, question types, and scoring system.\n*   **AWA Planning:** Even in a short time, you can improve your AWA score by having a template or framework in mind for how to approach the essays.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **This is an aggressive plan.**  Be prepared to dedicate a significant amount of time and effort.\n*   **Adjust the plan to your individual needs and learning style.**\n*   **Be realistic about your goals.** It's better to aim for a moderate score increase than to try to achieve a perfect score and burn out.\n*   **If possible, consider postponing the test if you feel unprepared.**  A few extra weeks of prep can make a big difference.\n\nGood luck! Remember that consistent effort and a strategic approach can make a significant difference in your GRE score.\n",
